        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Thursday</date>
                    <salute>My dear Hooker</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I got your note, just as I was setting out for the Geolog. Council.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Your invitation has tempted me much; owing to the Horners’ coming here Tuesday or Wednesday is the first day I c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. come. But will you oblige me by sending me <hi rend="underline">one</hi> line to say whether Gay<ref target="#foot.f3"/> speaks English, for to my shame &amp; utter disgrace I cannot speak French. When in Chile I talked with him in Spanish &amp; I now have forgotten that! So that if he cannot speak English, it w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be quite disagreeable to meet him &amp; I w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> much prefer visiting you in Spring, when the 4 to 5 hour’s drive would be pleasanter.</p>
<p>If he does not speak English &amp; therefore I do not come, pray remember me very kindly to him (though perhaps he has quite forgotten me) &amp; say I remember with much pleasure our short interviews.— I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> also much like to see M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Miers.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/> If I come, I will, (if convenient to you) come about 4 oclock on Wednesday &amp; return the middle of the next day.— You cannot well imagine what a bold step I feel this, I <hi rend="underline">literally</hi> have not slept out of <hi rend="underline">near</hi> relations house or inn for five years!!</p>
<p>I have not thanked you for a long &amp; as usual interesting letter, received some time since</p>
<p>Ever most truly yrs | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.3 My] ‘M’ <hi rend="italic">over illeg</hi></note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">For the basis of the date see n. 2, below.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s Account Book (Down House MS) records a payment on 6 February for a trip to London.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1830.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Claude Gay</ref>, who had travelled extensively in Chile during 1830 and 1831.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3322.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Miers</ref>, who worked as a botanist and engineer in South America, 1819–38. CD’s copy of Miers’ account of his travels (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5420.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Miers 1826</ref>) is in the Darwin Library–CUL.</note>
